# Compliance — do not modify casually

Wording on the donate page, the receipt email, and the compliance footer is legally constrained. Changes need treasurer (Eran) review before merging.

## Required disclosures on every donation surface

- Legal name "MOTIVE 4 ARTISTS INC." (uppercase, as filed with NY DOS).
- EIN.
- Tax-deductibility line: **"Donations are tax-deductible under §501(c)(3)."** (We hold our own determination, effective March 2, 2026 — there is no longer a fiscal sponsor or pending-status wording.)
- NY Charities Bureau §174-B disclosure with link to NY AG charities registration once filed (CHAR410, CHAR500).

## IRS substantiation rules

- Any single gift ≥ $250 requires a written acknowledgment with: amount, date, "no goods or services were received in exchange" line, and the org's name/EIN. Generated automatically by the receipt template.
- Quid-pro-quo gifts > $75 (e.g., gala tickets with a meal) require a fair-market-value statement.
- Year-end consolidated receipts go out by January 31.

## What goes in `<ComplianceFooter />`

A single reusable component used in the marketing layout. It carries the **lean** set only: legal name + EIN (one-line trust signal), the accessibility/privacy/terms link cluster, contact, social, and newsletter. Peer best practice (`docs/research/peer-website-benchmarking.md` §4.6) — no peer surfaces tax-status or §174-B in a global footer, and doing so crowds the footer without adding legal protection.

The legally-binding disclosures render on **solicitation surfaces** instead:

- The §501(c)(3) tax-deductibility line → `/donate` and the receipt email.
- `<CharitiesDisclosure />` (NY §174-B) → `/donate` and `/transparency`. Not gated on `irsStatus` — it must remain wherever we solicit.

Each piece of legal text lives in exactly one component under `components/compliance/`. Don't inline the wording anywhere else.
